 (0.35)_{stat} \\pm (0.34)_{sys} \\pm (0.06)_{theory}.\nThese findings agree within errors with theoretical predictions for both the\ntotal asymmetry and the form factor. In addition to the hydrogen measurement,\nthe asymmetry was measured at the same kinematics using a deuterium target. The\nasymmetry for deuterium was determined to be -43.6 \\pm (14.6)_{stat} \\pm\n(6.2)_{sys} ppm.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 7 Dec 2012 15:57:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-12-10"}
{"id":"1212.1711","submitter":"M\\`arius Josep Fullana i Alfonso","authors":"Antonio Alfonso-Faus and M\\`arius Josep Fullana i Alfonso","title":"Bekenstein and the Holographic Principle: Upper bounds for Entropy","comments":"4 pages, to be published in the \"Proceedings of the Spanish\n  Relativity Meeting in Portugal ERE2012: Progress in Mathematical Relativity,\n  Gravitation and Cosmology\" held at Guimar\\~aes 3-7 September 2012, by\n  Springer Proceedings in Mathematics","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Using the Bekenstein upper bound for the ratio of the entropy $S$ of any\nbounded system, with energy $E = Mc^2$ and effective size $R$, to its energy\n$E$ i.e. $S/E < 2\\pi k R/\\hbar c$, we combine it with the holographic principle\n(HP) bound ('t Hooft and Susskind) which is $S \\le \\pi k c^3R^2/\\hbar G$. We\nfind that, if both bounds are identical, such bounded system is a black hole\n(BH). For a system that is not a BH the two upper bounds are different. The\nentropy of the system must obey the lowest bound. If the bounds are\nproportional, the result is the proportionality between the mass M of the\nsystem and its effective size $R$. When the constant of proportionality is\n$2G/c^2$ the system in question is a BH, and the two bounds are identical. We\nanalyze the case for a universe. Then the universe is a BH in the sense that\nits mass $M$ and its Hubble size $R \\approx ct$, t the age of the universe,\nfollow the Schwarzschild relation $2GM/c^2 = R$. Finally, for a BH, the Hawking\nand Unruh temperatures are the same. Applying this to a universe they define\nthe quantum of mass $\\sim 10^{-66} g$ for our universe.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Dec 2012 22:21:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-12-11"}
{"id":"1212.1712","submitter":"Niels Kj{\\ae}rgaard","authors":"Ana Rakonjac, Kris O. Roberts, Amita B. Deb and Niels Kj{\\ae}rgaard","title":"Note: Computer controlled rotation mount for large diameter optics","comments":"3 pages, 4 figures, 1 movie link, supplementary files link, accepted\n  for publication in RSI","journal-ref":"Review of Scientific Instruments {\\bf 84} 026107 (2013)","doi":"10.1063/1.4791796","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ins-det","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We describe the construction of a motorized optical rotation mount with a 40\nmm clear aperture. The device is used to remotely control the power of large\ndiameter laser beams for a magneto-optical trap (MOT). A piezo-electric\nultrasonic motor on a printed circuit board (PCB) provides rotation with a\nprecision better than 0.03 deg and allows for a very compact design. The\nrotation unit is controlled from a computer via serial communication, making\nintegration into most software control platforms straightforward.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 7 Dec 2012 08:41:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 11 Dec 2012 03:20:21 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 29 Jan 2013 09:08:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-03-05"}
